	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>HERETIC'S BANE 3</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'>               <b>Heretic’s Bane</b>
                    Chapter 3

                 <p>By Tarendor</p>



<p>For the record: I HATE Freeport. It is a city that exudes Chaos. And even after several months of frequenting its less-than-clean streets, I can still get occasionally confused while trying to navigate its twisting, maze-like pathways. I suppose its fortunate that I have a well-developed sense of direction. While I wouldn’t call myself a ranger(who’d want to?), I’ve been able to find my way in some of Norrath’s more confusing locales. I’ve done quite a bit more travelling than I ever thought I would when I was a young and brash apprentice in the Tower of the GateCallers.</p>

<p>I suppose this is my favourite spot in all of Freeport(if I have to name one). High atop the battlements of the west gate, overlooking the constant traffic that the city receives and expels…somewhat like the overworked bellows of a busy blacksmith. Some of these travellers are despicable enough that I’d destroy them on sight. Still, most of them seem to have some sort of deal with the local militia. I’ve even seen Iksar in this place. Disgusting…but beyond my power to remedy, short of levelling the city itself.</p>

<p>I feel like this journal is falling behind. It seems like every time I add to it, a hundred more important things have sprung up in my life. I have NO idea where I’ll find the time to write it all down. Perhaps I should hire a scribe. Hmmm…no. That’s the sort of thing a stuck-up Wizard like Al’Kabor would do. </p>

<p>I’m not a very big fan of most of my Wizardly brethren. It’s got nothing to do with the art itself…but more with the attitude that comes with it. Wizards are arrogant and make no excuse for it other than their own self-assumed superiority. Al’Kabor’s almost god-like reputation among my Erudite brethren hasn’t made matters any better. I shudder to think what would happen if he ever really DID achieve a measure of immortality.</p>

<p>Well enough of that, this is a journal about my life…not an open forum for wizard-bashing…</p>

<p>It was around the fifth spire of my advancement when I met the wizard. It was early in the morning as I recall. Sunlight had just begun to penetrate the dense, green canopy of Toxullia forest and I had stepped out of the tunnel leading back to Erudin city to survey the forest before I set off.</p>

<p>Dismissing the wisp stone that I had conjured to light my way through the deep darkness of the tunnel, I breathed deeply of the forest air. It smelled as it always has: Of leaves, both dead and alive, permeated with a dampness that made the air thicker and so made one more conscious of each breath. It was touched with the scent of forest flowers, blooming in vegetative rapture to offer their own perfume to the domain of their life and death. And finally, one could also smell the scent of the denizens of the forest: snakes, large fire-beetles (hunted for their light-giving eyes, though not without peril), skunks (VERY evident), and even the kobolds which have called this place home for centuries.</p>

<p>Kidrian had once taught me, when I was still just a boy, a technique that allowed one to acclimate oneself to almost any given environment. It involved using each of the senses to almost literally reach out and acquire the sight, smell, taste, touch and sound of where you were. When he had first tried to teach me, I had laughed at the priest, telling him that if one were strong enough, like him, one could go anywhere without fear and do anything one desired without worry for safety.</p>

<p>He had then knelt in front of me, until we were eye to eye, and asked me just how strong ‘strong enough’ really was. I gave the best answer that my limited scope of learning at the time would allow(I WAS just a boy then) and told him with confidence that ‘strong enough’ was just that…being very powerful and able to stop others from hurting you because you had more power than they. It seemed a silly question for the priest to ask me. Then he told me that my father had been strong enough destroy him with very little effort, and asked if I thought that that fact should have protected him from the ones who murdered him.</p>

<p>His question had hurt me, I wasn’t sure why at the time. And I turned away from him, tears suddenly in my eyes and anger in my heart at this man who had been the only ‘father’ I could truly remember. I felt his hand on my shoulder but I didn’t turn back to face him. </p>

<p>I think that, looking back at it now, what had really upset me was the shattering of that image of my father as all powerful…and by extension that diminished my view of myself. I think it was at that point that I realized that I was a flesh and blood thing that could and would die if someone really wanted to accomplish it. Kidrian had made me lose a piece of my childhood innocence and it hurt me. I never laughed at one of his lessons again. I always looked for the wisdom and truth in them afterwards. My anger at him faded quickly and he was once again the replacement father that I had needed so desperately back then.</p>

<p>His lesson in reaching out with my senses has served me more times over the years than I can count. Allowing me to get myself into and out of  several bad situations. I miss you Kidrian…</p>

<p>It had only been a few minutes since I had emerged from the tunnel and stepped out onto the covered, stone platform where the gate guards stood their constant vigil over the forest entrance. I had thought that I was more or less alone, about to step off the low platform and head into the forest proper to begin my journey. I took one last breath and again concentrated on each of my senses, trying to detect any unusual change in the feel of the forest. </p>

<p>I whirled in the direction of the quiet footsteps that I suddenly heard, the protection of the nearby guards forgotten, and a spell coming to bear in my mind. And then I stopped and stared, and stared and stared some more as the most beautiful woman that I had ever seen came to a sudden stop just four feet away from me. </p>

<p>I was sure that my sudden movement had frightened her somewhat as well, although she assured me later that it hadn’t. As she took a step back and smiled slightly, I took in her face, framed by the hood of the red robe she wore which signalled her status as a fledgling wizard. Her rich, dark-brown eyes, and smooth skin. Perfectly formed lips, slightly parted and upturned at the corners as she smiled.</p>

<p>I was dimly aware that she had spoken but couldn’t for the life of me focus on what she had said. Finally, she reached up and gently touched my cheek asking: ‘Are you alright, sir?’</p>

<p>I shook my head slightly and then apologized, making an excuse of having my mind somewhere else. She smiled knowingly, as if this kind of reaction from men was typical, which made me feel even more a fool. Was I really so clumsy and inept around women as that back then? I suppose I was.</p>

<p>‘I don’t recall seeing you out here before,’ I said as I tried my best to stop staring. ‘This forest can be a dangerous place.’ I WAS lame back then.</p>

<p>‘Aye,’ she said, her smile becoming slightly grim, ‘But I have a companion with me for additional protection.’</p>

<p>As she gestured behind her, its safe to say that my heart sank several inches in my chest. The ‘companion’ she pointed out to me was a tall Erudite, dressed in what looked like wicker armor and brandishing a long sword and shield. The very picture, of a perfect hero.</p>

<p>My sigh must have been audible enough for her to hear because she raised an eyebrow at me and tilted her head slightly as she studied my face.</p>

<p>‘Is there something wrong?’ She asked me, the serious look of concern coming to her face not doing very much to diminish her beauty. My heart seemed to throb with a dull ache that spread to the rest of me.</p>

<p>I shook my head several times, and told her that I was just anxious to be off on my walk through the forest…as if I could even remember where I had intended to go. Hearts are the MOST foolish part of the anatomy. Whoever is reading this…note that well.</p> 

<p>‘Well don’t let us keep you then. Enjoy your walk.’ She said this to me as she motioned her companion over to us and quickly introduced him to me.</p>

<p>I am almost embarrassed to admit that I have forgotten his name. I’m usually very good with names. Which, of course, goes to point out just how scatter-brained her presence had made me.</p> 

<p>Her name though, I will never forget for as long as I live. Oniana. I still say it to myself sometimes…usually when I’m caught off-guard in a weak moment. Moments like that, I can ill afford these days. A lot has come to pass.</p>

<p>After asking my name in return(I was actually rather proud that I could give it without pause…see how dangerous emotions are?), she and the Paladin of Prexus (Damn, I WISH I could remember that name!) set off due south from the Erudin city entrance.</p> 

<p>I watched their leaving and realized that, given their direction, they were probably headed across the river to the Paineel side of the forest. I was suddenly gripped by the urge to stop them and ask if they knew what lay ahead of them if they continued south, but figured that they probably had a good idea and didn’t need advice from me.</p>

<p>Well alright, what I REALLY was thinking was that I didn’t want to look like an idiot in front of Oniana. Especially if they were capable of taking care of themselves and I was telling them things that they knew already.</p>

<p>Several long moments passed as I mulled things over in my mind before I finally decided what I’d do and how I’d do it.</p>

<p>I set off at a brisk pace headed due west of the gateway to the city. I hugged the north ridge closely, and when I judged that I was about halfway to the west ridge, I cut sharply south and ran all the way until I hit the beach. When I was at the shoreline, I turned east and headed that way, skirting the hut where a Necromancer made his home(old score to settle there…but a tale for another time), and continuing on my way toward the bridge that lead over to the Paineel half of Toxullia.</p>

<p>The scents and sounds of the forest kept me alert as I looked for signs of the trail of Oniana and her companion. Several of the weaker kobolds, runts really, passed me by but gave me a wide birth as I quickened my pace toward the bridge.</p> 

<p>As the white stone bridge came into view, I continued to glance around for any signs of the two but without success. However, in the soft earth at the end of the Erudin side of the bridge, I was able to make out two sets of footprints. They were recently made and pointed across the bridge.</p>

<p>Sighing, I quickly crossed and stopped to survey the forest around me. There was no doubt that the sinister feeling that crept into my bones was due to the proximity of the Heretics. At the time of course, I still didn’t know half of what I know today about them…but I was very aware of how I felt. And I felt uneasy to say the least.</p>

<p>I spotted fresh tracks headed due west from the bridge among those of the kobolds and other things which I feared to name then, even in my mind, and I followed them, convinced that they belonged to the pair.</p>

<p>This wasn’t actually my first time on the Heretic side of the forest, but it was the first time I had ever ventured over alone. It wasn’t a place for the faint hearted…or the uninformed. And the foolish? Well…enough of their bones now shambled around the forest, terrifying all who venture
therein. </p> 

<p>As I made my way west and slightly north, the tracks lead to a place that was now familiar to me. I’d like to say that brought me comfort, but the tracks lead straight toward a kobold camp. {Take note: this is just the kind of luck that has followed me throughout my entire career. And NO, I don’t know why.}</p>

<p>The sounds of fighting came to me as I approached the camp, but the remains of a large, stone wall(piece of an old ruin that has been there for centuries I imagine) stopped me from getting a view of what was going on.</p>

<p>I DID have the presence of mind not to rush into the fray though, so I pulled up short of rounding the slab of stone. I pulled a piece of malachite from the pocket of my robe, and taking a breath, I began to cast a spell of Calling. Energy from the very earth itself surged upward through my body, flowing out from my hands like a pale, green mist. Leaves began to swirl about me as the energy within me built and I reached out with my mind to the ether of the very world itself.</p>

<p>Fire I envisioned, and fire I sought. Filling my thoughts with it and beckoning to the very planet. Before me, on the forest floor, leaves and bits of twigs were picked up by a small tornado of wind as a gout of fire was spit from apparent nothingness there.</p>

<p>When the flame died down, a smallish creature seemingly made from liquid fire, with horns on its head and nothing below its waist save a whirling maelstrom of flames greeted me in a hollow voice: ‘I await, master.’ The malachite was now fine ash in my hand.</p>

<p>With the Fire Elementalkin following me closely, I rounded the corner to approach the camp. And there, of course, chaos awaited me…</p>

<p>I noticed the corpses first. Two kobold watchers lay prostrate on the ground. One was charred and blackened, the other was bleeding from various wounds scattered about its body. As I watched, it gave a last half-hearted swipe of its claws and lay still.</p>

<p>My eyes then turned toward the ongoing fray and sought out Oniana and her friend. The paladin was busy engaging both a kobold sentry and one of their shamans. His sword was a blur of movement as he blocked and parried, returning blow for blow. I could see, however, that he was not only bleeding from several wounds himself, but that he was beginning to tire. Sweat was pouring off him and he was breathing heavily with the effort of facing two foes.</p>

<p>My eyes then flicked off to the side to see Oniana, a gash in the sleeve of her robe surrounded by a growing wet spot from her own blood. She had the other arm raised high, however, and was busy blasting away at the shaman with a fiery spell. In her weakened state though, it was obvious that she couldn’t keep it up for long, and also obvious that the shaman wasn’t stupid. Telltale blue sparkles showed every now and then as he healed himself between her attacks.</p>

<p>I resisted the urge to rush to her side immediately and instead pointed at the shaman and commanded the Elementalkin to attack. With a fiery howl, the little creature rushed into battle, flaming fists battering the now-bewildered spirit-caller.</p>

<p>As soon as the two had clashed, I turned my attention to the sentry, who was still engaging the paladin and starting to with through. I quickly cleared my mind and sent a Burn spell into the fray. Concussive flame erupted under the sentry, burning through fur and flesh alike. Distracting it long enough for the paladin to raise his sword high and, with a roar drive the blade down between the creature’s neck and shoulder, stopping when it reached the general vicinity of its heart. I was rather impressed with his strength…if only I could remember his name…</p>

<p>In the meantime, my little flaming pet finished off the shaman with a fire  spell of its own which left the hyena-thing a smoking heap on the ground, before returning to my side. The smell of burning flesh began to get more than a little oppressive in that camp…</p>

<p>The paladin dropped to his knees…breathing heavily, as I turned to Oniana. Concentrating for a moment, I pulled several bandages from thin air and proceeded to wordlessly bind the wound on her arm, then I turned and started the same process on the paladin.</p>

<p>As I got one gash wrapped and started on another, I was about to sternly lecture them both about wandering around in Heretic territory when, of course, the skeletons attacked.</p>

<p>I was at first dimly aware of the Elementalkin casting a shield of flame on itself, then was MORE than aware of cackling laughter behind me as a bony fist swatted me aside, stunning me and sending dark spots to dance before my eyes.</p>

<p>Cradling my head in my hands, I struggled to focus as I turned to see the paladin rush in front of the skeleton and start to hack away at it with his blade. I was also in time to see Oniana wave her hands and send green runes to hold the other skeleton in place as my elemental attacked it with ferocious zeal.</p>

<p>I then saw her drop to her knees and close her eyes, and I realized in that moment that her magical energy was spent. Furthermore, the paladin wasn’t exactly spry and fresh, and the skeletons were full of the kind of terrible energy that only the undead can possess.</p>

<p>A long moment of cold panic gripped me. The Elementalkin wasn’t having nearly as easy a time with the skeleton as with the kobolds and with Oniana out of it, her superior combat spells couldn’t be factored into this fight. I knew though, that I had to do SOMETHING quickly.</p>

<p>Turning to the skeleton that faced the paladin, I sent a Burn spell its way, blasting pieces of bone and rotted flesh from its frame. That wouldn’t be nearly enough I knew…but I wanted to soften it up enough for what I was about to do next.</p>

<p>‘Don’t die on me now, knight!’ I shouted at the paladin, who looked ready to do just that. Still, his posture became a bit more erect and he looked more determined…if more than a bit frightened.</p>

<p>Judging the distance between the two undead things, I stepped squarely into the space between them and concentrated. A circular mat of flames surrounded my feet as I called the energy to me. And then I released it, my arms stretched wide and the thrill of the channelling drowning out the desperate urgency of the situation. Columns of screaming fire erupted beneath each skeleton, causing more bone chips to fly away from their bodies and blackening and charring their bones. </p>

<p>And then I did it again, and again. I became so focussed on the casting, so taken with the feel of power that I hardly noticed the skeletal forms  to either side of me shatter and fall to the scorched earth beneath them as the last Fire Flux died down. It was several minutes before I was myself again.</p>

<p>Looking around me, I quickly noticed the paladin searching the remains of the creatures for anything of value. Oniana started at me wide-eyed for a moment before coming over and putting her arms around me(I swear I could have stayed like that FOREVER), thanking me for saving their lives. The paladin came up and slapped me on the back, bruising a rib in the process I was sure at the time.</p>

<p>I turned to them both and sternly told them to follow me. And then we ran…all three of us, with the battered Elementalkin in tow. We didn’t stop until we had crossed the bridge and continued north again(I cast a quick True North spell to be sure), until we reached the gate to Erudin.</p>

<p>As soon as we were next to the tunnel entrance and the safety of the sentinels that guarded it, we collapsed in three sweaty, bloody heaps and stayed that way for a solid hour. Not talking much save for the occasional grunt of pain or rasping sigh of discomfort, the three of us seemed almost afraid to say anything.</p>

<p>‘Well,’ I said sitting up and stretching aching muscles that I was previously unaware of having, ‘Let’s not do THAT again anytime soon.’</p>

<p>The paladin raised a surprised eyebrow and Oniana suddenly burst into beautiful, sparkling laughter. I became aware at that point, with a certain rueful dread that I would do almost anything to hear that sound again…maybe even repeating the days events.{Did I mention yet how silly the human heart is? I suppose I have…}</p>

<p>The paladin departed back to his temple to recover and sell his share of the spoils. They offered me some, but I declined politely at that point. I told them that they’d need it and that I had recently come into a fair share of money myself.</p>

<p>As for Oniana and I…well the tale doesn’t quite end there. I learned that she was one spire lower in advancement than I was at that time…and that she was anxious to explore the world around her…and a lot of other things that I don’t think I’ll share right now.</p>

<p>We spent more and more time together after that. And eventually, we became nearly inseparable. It took me a while to admit to myself how I really felt about her…but she was a patient person, and she taught me to be as well. We BOTH learned from each other…and for that, I’ll always be grateful…no matter how much it hurts even now. There are tales upon tales that I could tell you about our adventures together. Maybe I will someday…but not this day. </p>

<p>No…THIS day, I have other business to attend to. There’s a certain druid waiting for me in the Oasis of Marr and I need to go find her before she pulls a sand giant’s beard or something similar.</p>

<p>Strange, but I didn’t think this would be so hard. Its just a recount of what’s gone before right? Nothing that I can change or alter in the least. Still, I seem to find the quill harder and harder to lift in some places…and then happily flitting along in others. I miss you Oniana…</p>
 




 </font></td>
	</tr>
